<bioghist>
<head>Biography</head>
<p>Ivoryton is one of three villages in the town of Essex, CT. The village was built up around the Comstock, Cheney &amp; Co. ivory processing plant as an example of industrial paternalism. Before the factory closed its doors in 1989, it was the main employer for village residents. The factory built or helped build a store, a school, the Ivoryton Library, the Ivoryton Playhouse and over 100 houses, as well as factory buildings that are now in use by other businesses.</p>
</bioghist>
<scopecontent>
<head>Scope and Content of Collection</head>
<p>This collection documents the history of the village of Ivoryton primarily, although some references to Centerbrook and Essex Village, the other two villages in the town of Essex, are included. These materials were acquired by the library through donations over the past several decades. Many are of unknown origin. Included are pamphlets, manuscripts, magazines and magazine articles, research papers, audiovisual materials, newsletters, legal documents, census reports, cookbooks, maps, scrapbooks, newspapers and newspaper clippings, postcards, photographs, documents and realia. While there are frequent mentions of Comstock, Cheney &amp; Co. and Pratt, Read &amp; Co., the two names for the ivory factory in town, ,the materials mainly show the history of the other business and organization. There are also personal reminiscences as well as a large amount of material on the Falls River Flood of 1982.</p>
</scopecontent>
<arrangement>
<head>Arrangement</head>
<p>This collection is divided into 3 series: Series I: Documents and Ephemera, Series II: Photographs and Postcards, Series III: Newspaper Clippings. As there was no original order and very little provenance, the items in this collection are artificially arranged first geographically, then by subject.</p>
</arrangement>
